<!-- Begin Title -->
<h1>Remainder</h1>
<!-- End Title -->
<hr class=3D"margin-t-1-8 margin-b-3-4">
<!-- Begin Total Content -->
<!-- Begin Content -->
<div class=3D"entry-content">
<p>
In general, a remainder is a quantity "left over" after performing a partic=
ular algorithm. The term is most commonly used to refer to the number left =
over when two
 integers are divided by each other in <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram=
.com/IntegerDivision.html">integer division</a>.
 For example, <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Re=
mainder/Inline1.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-w=
idth:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"66" height=3D"21" alt=3D"55\7=3D7">,
 with a remainder of 6. Of course in real division, there is no such thing =
as a remainder
 since, for example, <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equat=
ions/Remainder/Inline2.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100=
%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"116" height=3D"21" alt=3D"55/7=3D7+=
6/7">.
</p>
<p>
The term remainder is also sometimes applied to the <a href=3D"https://math=
world.wolfram.com/Residue.html">residue</a>
of a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Congruence.html">congruence</=
a>.
</p>
</div>
